Short answer (TL;DR)
Yes, “bribes” — i.e., validators re‑staking the TAO/Alpha they earn to fatten their own stake — are absolutely possible on TAO Hash.
They work because the protocol tells miners to aim their hash in proportion to each validator’s stake weight. When a validator ploughs its rewards back into stake, its weight goes up → the pie it can distribute every block gets bigger → miners shift more hash there.
So the validator’s self‑re‑stake is a standing bribe: “Point your rigs at me and I’ll keep making your pie larger.”

Sources are TAO Hash github + Bittensor docs

Where the repo spells this out @Nick [τ, τ] 

* Incentive Design section of the TAO Hash README:
“Validators evaluate the hashrate contributed by miners, and miners are incentivized to distribute their hashrate across validator pools proportionally to stake weight to maximise their expected return.” 

That one rule is enough to create the bribe loop:
- Validator restakes its earnings → stake weight increases.
- Its “reward pie” (Alpha emissions) grows because stake weight sets pie size.
- Miners re‑allocate hash toward that validator to chase the fatter pie.
- More hash → more fees/earnings for the validator → it can restake again.
- Nothing in the code forces validators to do this, but the economics make it smart if they want to win hashpower.

Here’s how the bribe loop actually works:

In TAO Hash, miners choose which validators to connect their hashpower to.
The more TAO a validator has staked, the more rewards it can distribute — so miners naturally aim for the biggest payouts.
When a validator uses its earnings to buy more TAO and restake it, its reward pool grows over time.
Miners don’t just notice — they respond to validators who publicly commit to restaking, because more stake means bigger rewards per terahash.
That restake loop is the validator’s “bribe”: spending today’s earnings to attract more miners (and earn even more) tomorrow.
